WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-US

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.760
I've covered FastAPI several times in my previous videos.

00:00:03.760 --> 00:00:06.840
Today, I'd like to dive in a bit deeper and talk about

00:00:06.840 --> 00:00:08.560
a few things that you typically won't

00:00:08.560 --> 00:00:10.920
find in most API tutorials online.

00:00:10.920 --> 00:00:13.440
I'm going to cover four things that will help you,

00:00:13.440 --> 00:00:15.080
especially if you want to create a backend

00:00:15.080 --> 00:00:17.080
that's used in a production setting.

00:00:17.080 --> 00:00:18.959
This video is sponsored by Pulumi,

00:00:18.959 --> 00:00:21.639
which is an infrastructure as code solution.

00:00:21.639 --> 00:00:24.000
I'll talk more about them later in the video.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:26.360
Now, let's dive into FastAPI.

00:00:26.360 --> 00:00:28.520
The example that I'm going to cover today is

00:00:28.559 --> 00:00:30.920
a simple FastAPI backend

00:00:30.920 --> 00:00:35.080
that has both items and automations.

00:00:35.080 --> 00:00:37.799
The items are just simple things

00:00:37.799 --> 00:00:39.119
that you can put in a database.

00:00:39.119 --> 00:00:40.480
So there are create, read, update,

00:00:40.480 --> 00:00:42.520
and delete operations on them.

00:00:42.520 --> 00:00:45.720
Next to that, you have automations that you can run

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:48.480
whenever something happens to an item.

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:51.799
And I've added a feature here where if you update the item,

00:00:51.799 --> 00:00:54.520
then some sort of automation is going to be run.

00:00:54.520 --> 00:00:57.360
And the idea of the automation is also pretty simple.

00:00:57.360 --> 00:01:00.040
It just runs a piece of Python code.

00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:02.000
You can, of course, build out these automations

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:05.680
more by adding things like triggers, webhooks,

00:01:05.680 --> 00:01:08.480
different paths, depending on certain conditions, et cetera.

00:01:08.480 --> 00:01:09.639
I'm not going to do that today.

00:01:09.639 --> 00:01:11.599
I'm going to keep it really simple.

00:01:11.599 --> 00:01:13.199
Here's a quick overview of the code.

00:01:13.199 --> 00:01:14.720
So we have a FastAPI app.

00:01:14.720 --> 00:01:15.760
It includes some routers.

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:17.440
I'm going to talk about that in a minute.

00:01:17.440 --> 00:01:19.599
And one part of the API

00:01:19.599 --> 00:01:21.480
is that there is a simple get request

00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:24.559
that just returns a response that the server is running.

00:01:24.559 --> 00:01:27.080
So I can start the server with uvcorn,

00:01:27.080 --> 00:01:29.239
which is a server running tool.

00:01:29.239 --> 00:01:30.320
It's very useful.

00:01:30.320 --> 00:01:33.519
And now it's running on localhost on port 8000.

00:01:33.519 --> 00:01:35.559
When I open the root URL in the browser,

00:01:35.559 --> 00:01:37.239
then this is what you get.

00:01:37.239 --> 00:01:40.360
Now, like I said, this has both items and automations.

00:01:40.360 --> 00:01:43.000
That's actually pretty easy to read items as well

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:43.839
in the browser.

00:01:43.839 --> 00:01:47.400
So I can simply type, for example, items one,

00:01:47.400 --> 00:01:49.720
and then it's going to return a JSON structure

00:01:49.720 --> 00:01:51.320
representing a particular item,

00:01:51.320 --> 00:01:52.839
in this case, a coffee machine.

00:01:52.839 --> 00:01:54.480
I'll cover the automation aspect

00:01:54.480 --> 00:01:56.839
of this API later on in the video.

00:01:57.599 --> 00:01:58.919
Now, the first thing that I want to show you

00:01:58.919 --> 00:02:00.919
is that if you have multiple endpoints,

00:02:00.919 --> 00:02:04.720
like items, automations, users, whatever,

00:02:04.720 --> 00:02:05.879
then it's going to be helpful

00:02:05.879 --> 00:02:08.919
to split these things up in different routes.

00:02:08.919 --> 00:02:12.000
And FastAPI has a router mechanism for that.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:13.199
And what this is going to do for you

00:02:13.199 --> 00:02:16.160
is that this will avoid you having to put all the routes

00:02:16.160 --> 00:02:17.839
into a single file.

00:02:17.839 --> 00:02:21.080
And unfortunately, most examples online

00:02:21.080 --> 00:02:23.320
explaining how to get started with FastAPI

00:02:23.320 --> 00:02:24.440
don't use routers.

00:02:24.440 --> 00:02:26.440
They simply put everything in the main file.

00:02:26.759 --> 00:02:29.720
So if you want to build a more complex API application,

00:02:29.720 --> 00:02:30.639
this is not going to work

00:02:30.639 --> 00:02:33.080
because your main file is going to be huge.

00:02:33.080 --> 00:02:36.759
So routers are a really good way of organizing this.

00:02:36.759 --> 00:02:37.600
So in the main file,

00:02:37.600 --> 00:02:41.600
you can see that I have here two routers that I've imported.

00:02:41.600 --> 00:02:43.080
There's the items router

00:02:43.080 --> 00:02:45.479
and there's the automations router.

00:02:45.479 --> 00:02:48.960
So these represent each a group of endpoints.

00:02:48.960 --> 00:02:50.399
And then in order to use them,

00:02:50.399 --> 00:02:51.919
I simply include them in the app

00:02:51.919 --> 00:02:54.160
using the include router methods.

00:02:54.160 --> 00:02:55.839
And then it knows these endpoints.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:57.479
And what I've created in the API

00:02:57.479 --> 00:03:00.479
is that I have here a routers folder

00:03:00.479 --> 00:03:02.559
where I have my various routers.

00:03:02.559 --> 00:03:04.520
So there's, for example, the items router,

00:03:04.520 --> 00:03:05.919
which looks like this.

00:03:05.919 --> 00:03:06.960
And there's some other things in here

00:03:06.960 --> 00:03:08.880
that I'm going to cover in a minute as well.

00:03:08.880 --> 00:03:09.880
So the first thing that you see

00:03:09.880 --> 00:03:12.679
is that I create a router, API router.

00:03:12.679 --> 00:03:16.119
This is a feature of FastAPI and I give it a prefix.

00:03:16.119 --> 00:03:19.360
So now any endpoints that are part of this router

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:21.919
fall under this prefix.

00:03:21.919 --> 00:03:24.639
That means, for example, if I have a get method,

00:03:24.639 --> 00:03:26.039
and then the item ID,

00:03:26.039 --> 00:03:28.279
it means you can get this by navigating

00:03:28.279 --> 00:03:32.119
to root URL slash items slash the ID.

00:03:32.119 --> 00:03:35.000
So slash item is put in front of every endpoint.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:37.080
And then each route simply contains the code

00:03:37.080 --> 00:03:39.720
that needs to be run when you call that endpoint.

00:03:39.720 --> 00:03:42.440
So it's creating an item, there's reading an item,

00:03:42.440 --> 00:03:45.440
there's reading item automations.

00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:47.039
So this reads the automations

00:03:47.039 --> 00:03:49.320
that are associated with an item.

00:03:49.320 --> 00:03:51.679
We have an update item function

00:03:51.679 --> 00:03:54.800
and we have a delete item endpoint.

00:03:54.800 --> 00:03:57.880
So that's how the items router is set up.

00:03:57.880 --> 00:04:01.240
And if you take a look at the automations router,

00:04:01.240 --> 00:04:03.280
is that actually pretty similar,

00:04:03.280 --> 00:04:07.080
except we have a different router with a different prefix.

00:04:07.080 --> 00:04:10.560
So here it's not slash items, but it's slash automations.

00:04:10.560 --> 00:04:12.960
And also here we have a create automation,

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:14.560
read automation,

00:04:14.560 --> 00:04:15.800
oh, scrolling too far,

00:04:15.800 --> 00:04:19.000
update automation and delete automation.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:20.480
And actually here's an error,

00:04:20.480 --> 00:04:22.879
this should be automation.

00:04:22.879 --> 00:04:25.160
Actually, FastAPI doesn't really care

00:04:25.160 --> 00:04:26.760
what the names of these functions are,

00:04:26.760 --> 00:04:28.980
but of course we should call this correctly.

00:04:28.980 --> 00:04:30.619
And it's all set up in a very similar way

00:04:30.640 --> 00:04:32.560
to how the items router is set up.

00:04:32.560 --> 00:04:34.519
That's why this function was called delete item

00:04:34.519 --> 00:04:36.320
because I just copy pasted everything.

00:04:36.320 --> 00:04:37.839
So in the items route, for example,

00:04:37.839 --> 00:04:41.879
create item needs an item create objects

00:04:41.879 --> 00:04:44.120
that contains all the information about the item.

00:04:44.120 --> 00:04:45.339
I'll show that in a minute.

00:04:45.339 --> 00:04:48.460
Then getting an item simply needs an item ID,

00:04:48.460 --> 00:04:50.560
which is in this case an integer.

00:04:50.560 --> 00:04:54.879
And reading item automations also only needs an item ID.

00:04:54.879 --> 00:04:57.679
And then it's going to return a list of automations.

00:04:57.679 --> 00:05:00.480
Updating an item needs an item update object,

00:05:01.339 --> 00:05:02.420
which contains information about the item.

00:05:02.420 --> 00:05:03.740
That'll also show in a minute.

00:05:03.740 --> 00:05:05.460
And then finally we have deleting the item

00:05:05.460 --> 00:05:07.140
that simply needs an item ID.

00:05:07.140 --> 00:05:08.299
And for automations,

00:05:08.299 --> 00:05:10.420
the way to set up is exactly the same.

00:05:10.420 --> 00:05:13.100
So if you create an API that has multiple groups

00:05:13.100 --> 00:05:15.339
of endpoints, like items, automations used,

00:05:15.339 --> 00:05:17.759
I really recommend that you use routers for this.

00:05:17.759 --> 00:05:19.060
So that's the first thing

00:05:19.060 --> 00:05:21.619
that's going to help you organize your code better.

00:05:21.619 --> 00:05:23.500
The second thing that you're not going to see

00:05:23.500 --> 00:05:27.379
in most examples online is that directly write the code

00:05:27.379 --> 00:05:29.259
that should happen if you call the endpoint

00:05:29.259 --> 00:05:31.519
inside the endpoint function.

00:05:31.519 --> 00:05:34.759
And if you're creating a more complex API application,

00:05:34.759 --> 00:05:37.199
that's not really a good way to do things.

00:05:37.199 --> 00:05:40.799
For one, the endpoint will then contain everything,

00:05:40.799 --> 00:05:42.799
which makes it harder to test.

00:05:42.799 --> 00:05:44.560
The second thing is that you're actually,

00:05:44.560 --> 00:05:45.400
if you're doing that,

00:05:45.400 --> 00:05:47.740
you're mixing up two responsibilities.

00:05:47.740 --> 00:05:50.119
You're mixing up routing,

00:05:50.119 --> 00:05:53.119
which is organizing where which endpoint is

00:05:53.119 --> 00:05:54.400
and how you should call it,

00:05:54.400 --> 00:05:58.299
together with the actual behavior of the endpoint code.

00:05:58.299 --> 00:05:59.799
And next to making things harder to test,

00:05:59.799 --> 00:06:01.640
that's also going to make things harder to read,

00:06:01.640 --> 00:06:02.600
because then, again,

00:06:02.600 --> 00:06:05.079
your files that contain all the routes

00:06:05.079 --> 00:06:07.479
for a particular router are going to get very long.

00:06:07.479 --> 00:06:08.680
And finally, you're not a problem

00:06:08.680 --> 00:06:12.719
with writing all that code in your endpoint function.

00:06:12.719 --> 00:06:14.480
That also means that if, let's say,

00:06:14.480 --> 00:06:16.799
you ever want to create a command line application,

00:06:16.799 --> 00:06:20.159
for example, that does the same things as your backend,

00:06:20.159 --> 00:06:22.719
then you have to copy paste all of that code,

00:06:22.719 --> 00:06:24.680
or you have to do a lot of refactoring work.

00:06:24.680 --> 00:06:27.240
So if you want to create a more complex API

00:06:27.260 --> 00:06:29.579
with lots of route groups

00:06:29.579 --> 00:06:31.460
containing lots of different routes,

00:06:31.460 --> 00:06:34.700
then you should also separate the routing part

00:06:34.700 --> 00:06:38.019
of your application from the actual operations.

00:06:38.019 --> 00:06:39.900
And this is actually what I've done here.

00:06:39.900 --> 00:06:42.219
So if you look at, let's say,

00:06:42.219 --> 00:06:46.180
let's take creating an item, which is here.

00:06:46.180 --> 00:06:47.620
So creating an item,

00:06:47.620 --> 00:06:51.100
the endpoint function is basically almost empty, right?

00:06:51.100 --> 00:06:53.260
It calls a create database item,

00:06:53.260 --> 00:06:55.180
which is the actual operation.

00:06:55.200 --> 00:06:57.560
It passes the item create object,

00:06:57.560 --> 00:06:59.279
show you what that is in a minute,

00:06:59.279 --> 00:07:02.560
and it also passes a link to the session,

00:07:02.560 --> 00:07:04.320
the database session.

00:07:04.320 --> 00:07:05.919
And then once that's done,

00:07:05.919 --> 00:07:08.879
then we have a database item object

00:07:08.879 --> 00:07:10.999
that create database item gives us,

00:07:10.999 --> 00:07:13.120
and then we transform that into something

00:07:13.120 --> 00:07:16.439
that FastAPI can return as a JSON structure.

00:07:16.439 --> 00:07:19.400
So the operation, which is all in this function,

00:07:19.400 --> 00:07:22.200
is completely separate from the actual endpoint.

00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:23.680
And I'm using another thing here

00:07:23.700 --> 00:07:27.100
that's also a really important part of FastAPI,

00:07:27.100 --> 00:07:28.540
which is dependency injection.

00:07:28.540 --> 00:07:32.620
So I provide a database session to the endpoint.

00:07:32.620 --> 00:07:35.180
And that means that I can write tests

00:07:35.180 --> 00:07:37.100
for this endpoint more easily.

00:07:37.100 --> 00:07:38.460
So how does this actually work?

00:07:38.460 --> 00:07:42.740
So in FastAPI, if I go to the database section of the code,

00:07:42.740 --> 00:07:46.700
what you can do is that I have here a basic database setup.

00:07:46.700 --> 00:07:49.040
So as you can see from the imports,

00:07:49.040 --> 00:07:50.900
this part is actually independent

00:07:50.900 --> 00:07:53.139
from the FastAPI tool, right?

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:56.680
It has some typing imports and it uses SQLAlchemy,

00:07:56.680 --> 00:07:59.240
which is an ORM to interact with the database.

00:07:59.240 --> 00:08:00.240
So it's completely separate

00:08:00.240 --> 00:08:01.960
from the routing aspect of the system,

00:08:01.960 --> 00:08:03.480
which is really important.

00:08:03.480 --> 00:08:06.439
So here I just use a simple SQLite database.

00:08:06.439 --> 00:08:07.840
So it contains a test database.

00:08:07.840 --> 00:08:10.639
You can change this to a SQL connection string

00:08:10.639 --> 00:08:11.840
if you want to,

00:08:11.840 --> 00:08:13.279
but then you'd have to make sure

00:08:13.279 --> 00:08:15.400
to not include the credentials in the code

00:08:15.400 --> 00:08:17.319
that should be in environment variables.

00:08:17.319 --> 00:08:19.479
So then using SQLAlchemy,

00:08:19.479 --> 00:08:23.660
I specify the models that are part of this database setup.

00:08:23.660 --> 00:08:25.380
So we have a declarative base,

00:08:25.380 --> 00:08:27.620
which is the core of SQLAlchemy.

00:08:27.620 --> 00:08:28.900
And then we have two things.

00:08:28.900 --> 00:08:31.220
We have a database item.

00:08:31.220 --> 00:08:34.919
So that corresponds to an items table in the database.

00:08:34.919 --> 00:08:39.180
And an item simply has an ID, a name, and a description.

00:08:39.180 --> 00:08:40.019
And that's it.

00:08:40.019 --> 00:08:43.560
And ID is a primary key and it's also an index.

00:08:43.560 --> 00:08:45.800
So that's database item, very basic.

00:08:45.800 --> 00:08:47.160
And then we have an automation.

00:08:47.160 --> 00:08:49.040
It's also very simple.

00:08:49.040 --> 00:08:52.200
We have an ID, which is again an integer.

00:08:52.200 --> 00:08:55.360
So it maps to a table automations.

00:08:55.360 --> 00:08:56.640
Forgot to mention that.

00:08:56.640 --> 00:08:59.140
So ID is also a primary key.

00:08:59.140 --> 00:09:01.720
And then we have the item ID,

00:09:01.720 --> 00:09:03.680
which is a reference to the item

00:09:03.680 --> 00:09:05.439
that the automation belongs to.

00:09:05.439 --> 00:09:06.640
And I simply specified it.

00:09:06.640 --> 00:09:08.040
This is a foreign key.

00:09:08.040 --> 00:09:11.480
It corresponds to the ID in the items table.

00:09:11.480 --> 00:09:13.279
And finally we have code.

00:09:13.279 --> 00:09:15.279
So this is the code that should be run

00:09:15.279 --> 00:09:17.400
when we want to run the automation.

00:09:17.400 --> 00:09:18.640
So that's all there is to it.

00:09:18.640 --> 00:09:20.199
That's the setup of the database.

00:09:20.199 --> 00:09:22.080
And then we have the part where we create

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:24.359
the connection with the database

00:09:24.359 --> 00:09:26.359
so that we can use that connection,

00:09:26.359 --> 00:09:28.280
use the session in FastAPI.

00:09:28.280 --> 00:09:31.159
So first we need to create a database engine.

00:09:31.159 --> 00:09:33.560
Then we need a session maker,

00:09:33.560 --> 00:09:36.199
something that can create sessions for us.

00:09:36.199 --> 00:09:37.600
And then we create the binding

00:09:37.600 --> 00:09:39.960
so that the engine knows that these models

00:09:39.960 --> 00:09:41.640
are actually going to be used

00:09:41.640 --> 00:09:45.319
in order to interact with the database by SQL Alchemy.

00:09:45.319 --> 00:09:49.519
And then finally we have a very simple dependency.

00:09:49.519 --> 00:09:52.040
So this is a function getDatabase

00:09:52.040 --> 00:09:54.920
that actually gives a database session.

00:09:54.920 --> 00:09:56.759
And I'm using a generator for this

00:09:56.759 --> 00:09:59.439
so that we can close the database automatically

00:09:59.439 --> 00:10:00.479
when we're done.

00:10:00.479 --> 00:10:03.000
And that's what this try finally block does here.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:06.519
So we yield the database session that we create here.

00:10:06.519 --> 00:10:07.920
And then finally,

00:10:07.920 --> 00:10:10.100
whether you get an exception or not doesn't matter.

00:10:10.100 --> 00:10:11.979
We're going to close the database.

00:10:11.979 --> 00:10:13.180
And that's good practice

00:10:13.180 --> 00:10:14.659
to always close database connections

00:10:14.659 --> 00:10:15.500
when you don't need them

00:10:15.500 --> 00:10:17.380
because these connections start to pile up

00:10:17.380 --> 00:10:19.140
and it's gonna slow down your database

00:10:19.140 --> 00:10:20.299
if you're not careful.

00:10:20.299 --> 00:10:23.180
So then how do we set up this dependency in FastAPI?

00:10:23.180 --> 00:10:25.699
Well, if you go, for example, to the items router,

00:10:25.699 --> 00:10:30.699
you see that we import the getDatabase function from here,

00:10:31.259 --> 00:10:34.780
and then we provide it as a dependency to the function.

00:10:34.780 --> 00:10:36.339
And then FastAPI will make sure

00:10:36.339 --> 00:10:37.979
that this function gets called

00:10:37.979 --> 00:10:39.579
whenever the endpoint is called.

00:10:39.579 --> 00:10:42.339
And that way we have always a database session.

00:10:42.339 --> 00:10:44.740
You also see that I pass the database session

00:10:44.740 --> 00:10:47.299
to the createDatabaseItem operation.

00:10:47.299 --> 00:10:50.699
So this function is what's doing the actual work

00:10:50.699 --> 00:10:51.580
in the database.

00:10:51.580 --> 00:10:52.860
And of course that makes sense

00:10:52.860 --> 00:10:54.860
because you can't work in database

00:10:54.860 --> 00:10:56.819
if you don't have a database session.

00:10:56.819 --> 00:10:59.399
So if you look at the actual implementation

00:10:59.399 --> 00:11:01.060
of these operations,

00:11:01.060 --> 00:11:02.819
that's actually what's happening here

00:11:02.819 --> 00:11:06.440
in items.pi under the DB folder.

00:11:06.440 --> 00:11:09.839
So we have here a couple of pedantic models

00:11:09.839 --> 00:11:11.759
that specify the information we need

00:11:11.759 --> 00:11:15.119
in order to communicate with this part of the application.

00:11:15.119 --> 00:11:18.160
So there is an item, which has an ID, name, and description.

00:11:18.160 --> 00:11:21.319
And by the way, these classes are also used by FastAPI

00:11:21.319 --> 00:11:25.880
to return JSON structures or read JSON data.

00:11:25.880 --> 00:11:28.199
So item, ID, name, and description,

00:11:28.199 --> 00:11:31.000
very similar to how the database has been set up.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:34.520
And then we also have item create and item update.

00:11:34.520 --> 00:11:35.920
So in order to create an item,

00:11:36.360 --> 00:11:38.039
we need to provide a name and description.

00:11:38.039 --> 00:11:40.119
Description is optional, it's not necessary.

00:11:40.119 --> 00:11:41.720
And if we update an item,

00:11:41.720 --> 00:11:44.080
we can provide either a name or description.

00:11:44.080 --> 00:11:45.800
So we can update either one of them.

00:11:45.800 --> 00:11:48.119
And then we have the actual operation.

00:11:48.119 --> 00:11:50.880
So createDatabaseItem, for example,

00:11:50.880 --> 00:11:53.839
well, it creates a DB item object.

00:11:53.839 --> 00:11:54.679
So that's...

00:11:54.679 --> 00:12:01.479
an actual ORM model and then it uses the session to create this database item and it also returns

00:12:01.479 --> 00:12:06.839
this as a result. So you can read it and do something with it. Updating a database item

00:12:06.839 --> 00:12:11.478
also has its own code for performing that operation. So I'm first reading the database

00:12:11.478 --> 00:12:16.439
item and I'm actually reusing another operation for that. So that's the one that's here. So this

00:12:16.999 --> 00:12:23.238
queries the database and then filters it on the item ID, returns the first one. If it's not found

00:12:23.238 --> 00:12:28.999
it raises a not found error. Then updating the database item, use that to get the database item,

00:12:28.999 --> 00:12:34.519
it sets the attributes and then commits that in a session. And finally what this update

00:12:34.519 --> 00:12:39.239
operation also does is that it runs the automations, which is another part of the

00:12:39.239 --> 00:12:42.759
system that I mentioned in the beginning. So I'll just include this as a simple example.

00:12:42.759 --> 00:12:47.559
You may want to run automations in different places as well but this allows you, for example,

00:12:47.559 --> 00:12:52.438
to execute some custom code whenever an item in a database is updated. And that can be helpful,

00:12:52.438 --> 00:12:57.239
for example, if you build a webshop then if an item in the database is updated then maybe you

00:12:57.239 --> 00:13:02.278
want to run automatically some code that also updates the item's description on your website.

00:13:02.278 --> 00:13:08.598
Just a minor design remark and that's more about where you place the boundaries. So what I've done

00:13:08.598 --> 00:13:15.719
here is that the input of these functions is a pedantic base model. It's an item create or an

00:13:15.719 --> 00:13:22.198
item update or simply an integer, right? Item ID. But it returns a database item in a way that

00:13:22.198 --> 00:13:26.359
doesn't make a lot of sense because you would expect actually that this thing would then also

00:13:26.359 --> 00:13:32.999
return an item, right? It should return something of this base model because then if you call the

00:13:32.999 --> 00:13:37.558
function you don't deal with the database at all. It's completely hidden. So I haven't done that in

00:13:37.558 --> 00:13:43.558
this particular example because I'm reusing read database item and using that in other functions

00:13:43.638 --> 00:13:49.638
as well. But probably it would be even better if each of these functions returns actually an

00:13:50.439 --> 00:13:52.439
item and not a database item.

00:13:52.439 --> 00:13:58.939
And then I would simply create an internal function to read a database item that I can reuse in these endpoints.

00:13:58.939 --> 00:14:06.439
That would probably be better because then in the routers, I also wouldn't need to do this conversion step here

00:14:06.439 --> 00:14:10.939
and knowing about how database items are being implemented.

00:14:10.939 --> 00:14:13.439
So in the current implementation, this is not ideal.

00:14:13.439 --> 00:14:15.439
But this is actually something that's really easy to fix.

00:14:15.439 --> 00:14:17.439
For example, let's take this function.

00:14:17.439 --> 00:14:23.119
and make a copy of that and then let's just keep this for internal use and now

00:14:23.119 --> 00:14:26.679
this one we can change so that it returns an item and what we then can

00:14:26.679 --> 00:14:31.359
simply do is take part of the read item code

00:14:31.359 --> 00:14:34.719
like this, and then let's...

00:14:34.719 --> 00:14:43.479
change this so that it returns this and then here I'm simply going to use the

00:14:43.479 --> 00:14:47.639
readDatabaseItem that passes the item ID and the session.

00:14:47.639 --> 00:14:49.719
So now I have this new function

00:14:49.719 --> 00:14:52.119
that already converts this to an item.

00:14:52.119 --> 00:14:55.639
And then in my router, I don't need to do this anymore.

00:14:55.639 --> 00:14:56.899
I can simply do this.

00:14:56.899 --> 00:15:05.899
like so. And now this is even simpler. And then of course you can change the other endpoints as well, so that it works like this.

00:15:05.899 --> 00:15:12.899
So for example, creating a database item, I can also simply return the item, like so.

00:15:12.899 --> 00:15:18.819
and then in the router I can simply do this.

00:15:18.819 --> 00:15:21.819
And you can do the same thing for the other operations as well.

00:15:21.819 --> 00:15:26.819
So you can imagine that sometimes it can be hard to determine what the exact boundaries are...

00:15:26.819 --> 00:15:31.819
...of what an operation should get as input and what it should return as a result...

00:15:31.819 --> 00:15:36.819
...and how it interacts with the database and what routers should or shouldn't know.

00:15:36.819 --> 00:15:41.819
Because there might also be a disadvantage to actually returning items and not database items.

00:15:41.819 --> 00:15:45.819
For example, if you combine different operations in your router endpoints...

00:15:45.819 --> 00:15:51.819
...then you may want to pass a database item between the operations for efficiency purposes.

00:15:51.819 --> 00:15:53.819
If you return an item, you can't do that.

00:15:53.819 --> 00:15:58.819
You then might need to do multiple database requests to get the information that you actually need.

00:15:58.819 --> 00:16:02.819
A third thing that you won't see in many examples online...

00:16:02.819 --> 00:16:06.819
...is that they don't really talk about deployment all that much.

00:16:06.819 --> 00:16:11.819
So whenever you start working on a new application, you may not even think about that yourself...

00:16:11.819 --> 00:16:16.819
...and then think, you know, I first build the thing and then I'll start thinking about how to actually deploy it.

00:16:16.819 --> 00:16:18.819
Actually, what I like to do is the other way around.

00:16:18.819 --> 00:16:25.819
I like to set up the scaffolding first before actually doing too much in the code.

00:16:25.819 --> 00:16:31.819
So typically what I would do if I, let's say, I want to create a new back-end API that I want to host in the cloud...

00:16:31.819 --> 00:16:35.819
...so what I will do is that I won't build out the complete API locally...

00:16:35.819 --> 00:16:42.819
...but I'll first start with, let's say, only the health check endpoints, just an empty GET request...

00:16:42.819 --> 00:16:48.819
...and then set up the whole scaffolding, including the whole deployment, CICD pipeline...

00:16:48.819 --> 00:16:53.819
...settings that you need in the cloud, everything to actually run this API...

00:16:53.819 --> 00:16:58.819
...and deploy it to the cloud whenever you push a new version to the main branch.

00:16:58.819 --> 00:17:03.819
And the reason why I do it that way, why I don't build out the complete API and then think about deployment...

00:17:03.819 --> 00:17:06.819
...is that I want to make sure that all the pieces fit together.

00:17:06.819 --> 00:17:12.819
And in my experience, this part, setting up the scaffolding and deployment and everything...

00:17:12.819 --> 00:17:15.819
...is often the most tricky to get right.

00:17:15.819 --> 00:17:22.819
Because you will have to create things like Docker files with the various imports and dependencies...

00:17:22.819 --> 00:17:24.819
...and there's many things that can go wrong.

00:17:24.819 --> 00:17:28.819
There's also many things that can go wrong with setting secrets up correctly...

00:17:28.819 --> 00:17:30.819
...so that you have access to the right credentials.

00:17:30.819 --> 00:17:37.819
Enabling APIs in your cloud provider so that you can actually host your API in the way that you want to in the cloud.

00:17:37.819 --> 00:17:41.819
So there's lots of things that can go wrong, lots of things that you need to set up...

00:17:41.819 --> 00:17:45.819
...and it can be very frustrating if you wait with that until the last minute.

00:17:45.819 --> 00:17:48.819
Because it's possible that due to some dependency that you're using...

00:17:48.819 --> 00:17:52.819
...that it actually blocks being able to deploy it properly to the cloud.

00:17:52.819 --> 00:17:55.819
So I find it's important to set this up as soon as possible...

00:17:55.819 --> 00:17:59.819
...and basically deal with the potential problems as soon as possible.

00:17:59.819 --> 00:18:05.819
So that afterwards, once it's set up, then it's pretty easy to build out the API and add more features to it.

00:18:05.819 --> 00:18:07.819
For deployment, you can use different tools.

00:18:07.819 --> 00:18:09.819
One that I'd like to use is Pulumi.

00:18:09.819 --> 00:18:11.819
They're also the sponsor of this video.

00:18:11.819 --> 00:18:14.819
Pulumi is what's called an infrastructure as code tool.

00:18:14.819 --> 00:18:18.819
And that means you can define what your cloud infrastructure looks like...

00:18:18.819 --> 00:18:22.819
...and handle provisioning those resources by actually writing code...

00:18:22.819 --> 00:18:24.819
...using your favorite programming language.

00:18:24.819 --> 00:18:28.819
So you can use Python, for example, to define what your infrastructure looks like.

00:18:28.819 --> 00:18:30.819
And I find that really helpful.

00:18:30.819 --> 00:18:33.819
In this particular API, what I've done is I've created a Dockerfile.

00:18:33.819 --> 00:18:34.819
So that's what I see here.

00:18:34.819 --> 00:18:36.819
So it's built on Python 3.11.

00:18:36.819 --> 00:18:38.819
And actually, the Dockerfile is pretty basic.

00:18:38.819 --> 00:18:42.819
So I simply install the dependencies, I copy the scripts to the folder...

00:18:42.819 --> 00:18:47.819
...and then I simply start the server just like I would do on my local machine.

00:18:47.819 --> 00:18:51.819
But then I have a main file, which is a Python file...

00:18:51.819 --> 00:18:55.819
...that actually specifies how to create the resources in the cloud.

00:18:55.819 --> 00:18:58.819
And being able to do this in Python, I find this very helpful...

00:18:58.819 --> 00:19:01.819
...because it simplifies the workflow a lot, in my opinion.

00:19:01.819 --> 00:19:05.819
So there's a couple of helper functions, like creating a registry...

00:19:05.819 --> 00:19:08.819
...where we're going to host the Docker image that we're going to build.

00:19:08.819 --> 00:19:11.819
Then we have a function for building an image.

00:19:11.819 --> 00:19:15.819
So this all relies on Pulumi's libraries.

00:19:15.819 --> 00:19:18.819
This uses Pulumi Docker, for example, so it creates an image.

00:19:18.819 --> 00:19:20.819
And I'm also passing some build arguments...

00:19:20.819 --> 00:19:24.819
...because I'm running this on a Mac which has Apple Silicon.

00:19:24.819 --> 00:19:28.819
So I need to make sure that it builds for Linux AMD64 processors...

00:19:28.819 --> 00:19:30.819
...otherwise it won't work.

00:19:30.819 --> 00:19:32.819
And then I'm hosting this application in the cloud...

00:19:32.819 --> 00:19:34.819
...using Google's CloudRum service.

00:19:34.819 --> 00:19:37.819
So here I'm using the Pulumi package for Google Cloud.

00:19:37.819 --> 00:19:40.819
Then I have a function that sets the right access policy...

00:19:40.819 --> 00:19:42.819
...so that it's actually publicly available.

00:19:42.819 --> 00:19:46.819
And finally, I have a main file where I call these functions...

00:19:46.819 --> 00:19:48.819
...and deploy the actual application.

00:19:48.819 --> 00:19:50.819
So I create a registry.

00:19:50.819 --> 00:19:54.819
Then I'm going to get the information about the registry, build an image...

00:19:54.819 --> 00:19:57.819
...create the CloudRum service, create the access policy...

00:19:57.819 --> 00:19:59.819
...and then export the important information...

00:19:59.819 --> 00:20:03.819
...like what is the URL of the CloudRum service, for example...

00:20:03.819 --> 00:20:05.819
...or what was the image name that was generated...

00:20:05.819 --> 00:20:07.819
...so I can find it back easily.

00:20:07.819 --> 00:20:09.819
And then what's really nice with Pulumi is that it's really easy...

00:20:09.819 --> 00:20:11.819
...to then deploy your application to the cloud.

00:20:11.819 --> 00:20:14.819
So you simply write Pulumi up...

00:20:14.819 --> 00:20:17.819
...and then it will set up all these things in the cloud for you.

00:20:17.819 --> 00:20:19.819
What's nice about an infrastructure-as-code solution...

00:20:19.819 --> 00:20:22.819
...is that you can do things with it that aren't possible...

00:20:22.819 --> 00:20:24.819
...if you define your infrastructure statically.

00:20:24.819 --> 00:20:28.819
And this is actually how I built the automation part of this example.

00:20:28.819 --> 00:20:30.819
So here you see what the code looks like...

00:20:30.819 --> 00:20:33.819
...when I want to run an actual automation from code in the cloud.

00:20:33.819 --> 00:20:36.819
And what I'm doing is that on the fly...

00:20:36.819 --> 00:20:38.819
...whenever I want to run a piece of code...

00:20:38.819 --> 00:20:41.819
...I create a sandbox environment, a serverless function in the cloud...

00:20:41.819 --> 00:20:43.819
...that actually runs that code.

00:20:43.819 --> 00:20:46.819
And then right after that, I immediately destroy the function again.

00:20:46.819 --> 00:20:50.819
So this allows me to run code in an isolated environment...

00:20:50.819 --> 00:20:52.819
...and then destroy that environment immediately...

00:20:52.819 --> 00:20:56.819
...so it doesn't affect other parts of my backend.

00:20:56.819 --> 00:20:58.819
If you were to run automation code directly in your backend...

00:20:58.819 --> 00:20:59.819
...it might be dangerous...

00:20:59.819 --> 00:21:01.819
...because if that code breaks your backend server...

00:21:01.819 --> 00:21:03.819
...then, well, you have a problem.

00:21:03.819 --> 00:21:06.819
So if you do it in an isolated environment, that's much better.

00:21:06.819 --> 00:21:07.819
And that's actually what I'm doing here.

00:21:07.819 --> 00:21:09.819
So the first step is, again, some scaffolding work...

00:21:09.819 --> 00:21:11.819
...preparing a virtual environment.

00:21:11.819 --> 00:21:14.819
So as you can see, I'm directly calling Python here to create a VM.

00:21:14.819 --> 00:21:15.819
And then I install the requirements.

00:21:15.819 --> 00:21:18.819
And then I have the function that runs all the automations.

00:21:18.819 --> 00:21:20.819
So I get the code from the automation...

00:21:20.819 --> 00:21:23.819
...and then I'm using Pulumi's automation framework...

00:21:23.819 --> 00:21:27.819
...to actually, on the fly, create a cloud resource.

00:21:27.819 --> 00:21:28.819
So that's what's happening here.

00:21:28.819 --> 00:21:31.819
So I prepare a virtual environment by calling that function.

00:21:31.819 --> 00:21:33.819
Then I create a new stack.

00:21:33.819 --> 00:21:35.819
So Pulumi works with different stacks...

00:21:35.819 --> 00:21:37.819
...like a development stack or a production stack.

00:21:37.819 --> 00:21:39.819
In this case, I create a development stack.

00:21:39.819 --> 00:21:41.819
And then I'm updating the stack.

00:21:41.819 --> 00:21:44.819
So this is going to create the resources in the cloud for me.

00:21:44.819 --> 00:21:49.819
And then what I get as a result from doing that is a function URL.

00:21:49.819 --> 00:21:52.819
So I create a cloud function, and this gives me a URL.

00:21:52.819 --> 00:21:55.819
And then next step is that I actually invoke the function...

00:21:55.819 --> 00:21:58.819
...passing the code of the automation.

00:21:58.819 --> 00:22:01.819
And then as a final step, I destroy the stack again.

00:22:01.819 --> 00:22:03.819
And how I've set this up is that next to the API...

00:22:03.819 --> 00:22:06.819
...I have a simple code runner setup...

00:22:06.819 --> 00:22:10.819
...which is basically another service that has a very simple main file...

00:22:10.819 --> 00:22:13.819
...that basically has a run code function...

00:22:13.819 --> 00:22:16.819
...that gets the actual code to run from JSON.

00:22:16.819 --> 00:22:20.819
It captures whatever we write to the standard out or standard error.

00:22:20.819 --> 00:22:22.819
And then it returns that as a result.

00:22:22.819 --> 00:22:25.819
And this is simply another infrastructure as code setup...

00:22:25.819 --> 00:22:29.819
...that deploys a cloud function using Pulumi.

00:22:29.819 --> 00:22:32.819
And then when you actually update an item and run the automation...

00:22:32.819 --> 00:22:36.819
...you see that it actually runs the code part of the automations...

00:22:36.819 --> 00:22:39.819
...in the cloud function and returns that as a result.

00:22:39.819 --> 00:22:42.819
So infrastructure as code allows you to do these kind of things dynamically...

00:22:42.819 --> 00:22:44.819
...and it opens up a lot of possibilities.

00:22:44.819 --> 00:22:46.819
If you want to try out Pulumi, it's free.

00:22:46.819 --> 00:22:48.819
You can simply go to pulumi.com.

00:22:48.819 --> 00:22:50.819
The link is also in the description of this video.

00:22:50.819 --> 00:22:54.819
A final important thing to think about is that when you deploy your API...

00:22:54.819 --> 00:22:57.819
...you also need to make sure that people can't abuse it.

00:22:57.819 --> 00:22:59.819
There are several things you can do.

00:22:59.819 --> 00:23:02.819
One is that you can create an authentication flow using OAuth...

00:23:02.819 --> 00:23:05.819
...and bearer tokens and API keys so that you know who it is.

00:23:05.819 --> 00:23:07.819
You can restrict access using scopes.

00:23:07.819 --> 00:23:10.819
That's all part of the OAuth standard.

00:23:10.819 --> 00:23:13.819
And that's one way to make sure that your users don't have access...

00:23:13.819 --> 00:23:15.819
...to things that they shouldn't have access to.

00:23:15.819 --> 00:23:19.819
So whenever you're creating a more complicated production-level API...

00:23:19.819 --> 00:23:23.819
...you should definitely also add some sort of authentication flow.

00:23:23.819 --> 00:23:25.819
And authentication flows are a whole other topic.

00:23:25.819 --> 00:23:29.819
If you'd like me to do a video about that, let me know in the comments.

00:23:29.819 --> 00:23:32.819
So adding authentication is important, but that's not the only thing you should do.

00:23:32.819 --> 00:23:36.819
Because A, that doesn't help if you're developing a public API...

00:23:36.819 --> 00:23:38.819
...or if your API has public endpoints.

00:23:38.819 --> 00:23:44.819
And B, it also doesn't preclude users from sending out way too many requests in a row.

00:23:44.819 --> 00:23:47.819
And if you want to deal with that, the best thing to do...

00:23:47.819 --> 00:23:50.819
...is to add a rate limiter to your backend API...

00:23:50.819 --> 00:23:56.819
...so that you can restrict the number of times users or anybody can call your endpoints.

00:23:56.819 --> 00:23:58.819
So how does a rate limiter typically work?

00:23:58.819 --> 00:24:03.819
Well, it's going to look at things like the ID of your machine, the IP address...

00:24:03.819 --> 00:24:06.819
...things like that to make sure you're not from a single machine...

00:24:06.819 --> 00:24:09.819
...sending thousands of requests per second.

00:24:09.819 --> 00:24:13.819
So FastAPI doesn't have direct built-in support for rate limiting...

00:24:13.819 --> 00:24:16.819
...but there are packages that integrate really well with FastAPI.

00:24:16.819 --> 00:24:20.819
And one of them is SlowAPI, and that's actually the rate limiter that I'm using here.

00:24:20.819 --> 00:24:22.819
So setting up SlowAPI is really simple.

00:24:22.819 --> 00:24:26.819
You just need to add an exception handler for RateLimitExceeded.

00:24:26.819 --> 00:24:28.819
That's an error type from SlowAPI.

00:24:28.819 --> 00:24:32.819
And then you need to pass it the handler that handles that particular error.

00:24:32.819 --> 00:24:37.819
And then what you can do in your routers or in your simple endpoints...

00:24:37.819 --> 00:24:39.819
...is that you can add limiters.

00:24:39.819 --> 00:24:40.819
So here's how that's set up.

00:24:40.819 --> 00:24:43.819
So SlowAPI has a limiter class.

00:24:43.819 --> 00:24:46.819
And we can indicate how we want to determine...

00:24:46.819 --> 00:24:51.819
...how the limiter is going to detect that a request comes from a different user.

00:24:51.819 --> 00:24:55.819
And I'm using the GetRemoteAddress function for that...

00:24:55.819 --> 00:24:59.819
...that looks at the remote address of the machine that's doing the API call.

00:24:59.819 --> 00:25:01.819
So that creates the limiter.

00:25:01.819 --> 00:25:04.819
And then in my router, I import this limiter.

00:25:04.819 --> 00:25:08.819
And then I'm using it as a decorator to define how often we can request that.

00:25:08.819 --> 00:25:12.819
And here we put a limit of one per second.

00:25:12.819 --> 00:25:16.819
And since the limiter needs to access the actual request in order to extract the information...

00:25:16.819 --> 00:25:21.819
...you need to also make sure to pass it as an argument to your endpoint function.

00:25:21.819 --> 00:25:22.819
Otherwise, this doesn't work.

00:25:22.819 --> 00:25:27.819
So this way, we've now defined a limiter for this particular endpoint.

00:25:27.819 --> 00:25:29.819
And then you can do this for every endpoint.

00:25:29.819 --> 00:25:31.819
And you can specify different types of limits.

00:25:31.819 --> 00:25:36.819
So, for example, if you want creating an item to be one request per second...

00:25:36.819 --> 00:25:39.819
...but reading an item, you may want to do that more.

00:25:39.819 --> 00:25:41.819
So you want to put the limits maybe a bit higher.

00:25:41.819 --> 00:25:47.819
At 10 per second, it's really easy to change this in the limiter specification.

00:25:47.819 --> 00:25:49.819
There's one minor caveat to take into account.

00:25:49.819 --> 00:25:53.819
It's that you need to specify these decorators in the right order.

00:25:53.819 --> 00:25:57.819
So limiter needs to be below the router.getDecorator.

00:25:57.819 --> 00:25:59.819
Otherwise, this won't work correctly.

00:25:59.819 --> 00:26:03.819
So these are just some of the things you need to think about when you create a production API.

00:26:03.819 --> 00:26:07.819
So, first, split your endpoints into separate routers...

00:26:07.819 --> 00:26:10.819
...so that the code becomes more manageable.

00:26:10.819 --> 00:26:14.819
Also, move operations out of the endpoint functions...

00:26:14.819 --> 00:26:16.819
...so that you can more easily test them...

00:26:16.819 --> 00:26:19.819
...and more easily reuse them in other types of applications...

00:26:19.819 --> 00:26:21.819
...such as a command line interface.

00:26:21.819 --> 00:26:24.819
The third point is that you need to think about deployment of your application.

00:26:24.819 --> 00:26:28.819
Set up the scaffolding first, because that's going to lead to most of the issues.

00:26:28.819 --> 00:26:29.819
It's going to take up most of the time.

00:26:29.819 --> 00:26:31.819
So do that as the first step.

00:26:31.819 --> 00:26:33.819
And the fourth one is that you need some way to control access.

00:26:33.819 --> 00:26:37.819
So whether that's an authentication flow, or using a limiter, or both...

00:26:37.819 --> 00:26:42.819
...that's really important to think about in order to make your APIs scalable and safe.

00:26:42.819 --> 00:26:45.819
Now, the fifth thing that I didn't talk about at all in this video...

00:26:45.819 --> 00:26:48.819
...is that you need to actually write software tests.

00:26:48.819 --> 00:26:50.819
When you write your test for your FastAPI backend...

00:26:50.819 --> 00:26:53.819
...there are a couple of things you can do to make your life a lot easier.

00:26:53.819 --> 00:26:58.819
If you want to learn about that, watch this video next, where I dive into the details.

00:26:58.819 --> 00:27:00.819
Thanks for watching, and see you soon.

